President Donald Trump has announced his intent to nominate Ronald Douglas Johnson as the Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary of the United States of America to the Republic of El Salvador. Johnson has served in the United States Government for over three decades, including as a Colonel in the United States Army and as a member of the intelligence community. Currently, he is the Central Intelligence Agency's Science and Technology Liaison to the United States Special Operations Command. Johnson has worked on various regional issues, such as refugees, counternarcotics, counterterrorism, human rights, and tropical virus disease control. He holds a B.S. from the University of the State of New York and an M.S. from the National Intelligence University, and he speaks Spanish.

Additionally, Donald W. Washington has been nominated as the Director of the United States Marshal Service, Department of Justice. Washington is a Partner at the Jones Walker Law Firm and specializes in litigating business, energy, white-collar crime, and healthcare issues. He previously served as the United States Attorney for the Western District of Louisiana and was the Chief Federal Law Enforcement Official for the district. Washington has also served on various Department of Justice committees, including those on Civil Rights, Controlled Substances, and Native American Issues. He graduated from the United States Military Academy and served in the United States Army and Army Reserve. He earned a J.D. from South Texas College of Law.